{"title_page": "Charles Rous-Marten", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n[[File:Charles Rous-Marten.jpg|thumb|Photograph of Charles Rous-Marten from his Obituary in The Engineer]]'''Charles Rous-Marten''' (1842\u20131908) was a New Zealand journalist and British railway writer and recorder.\n\nHe was born in England. At the age of 16 his family emigrated to New Zealand, settling in [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]. In 1864 he was appointed Meteorological Director of [[Southland Province]],<ref>''Southland Times'', 18 Oct 1864, p.5</ref> a position he held until 1870. He was employed as a journalist with ''[[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]]'' in Wellington about 1876 and was later editor, resigning in 1884. He was editor of ''[[The New Zealand Times]]'', also in Wellington, from 1885 to 1890. In that year he was appointed London correspondent for a number of leading New Zealand newspapers in the New Zealand Associated Press, which he continued to do until shortly before he died.<ref>''Press'', 23 Apr 1908, p.7</ref>\n\nHe took a close interest in railways over many years and in 1884 and 1885 he did a thorough study of the British rail network, involving around 40,000 miles of travel. In 1887 the results were embodied in a report to the New Zealand Minister of Public Works entitled [http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-52019982/view;''Notes on the Railways of Great Britain''], which received favourable reviews.<ref>''Otago Daily Times'', 9 Jul 1908, p.12</ref>\n\nHe is chiefly known for recording a speed of 102.3&nbsp;mph on the 'Ocean Mail' special from Plymouth to London hauled by [[Great Western Railway|GWR]] locomotive [[GWR 3700 Class 3440 City of Truro|3440 City of Truro]] on 9 May 1904,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.heritagerailway.co.uk/news/could-it-ever-be-better-than-this |title= Could it ever be better than this? |date= 6 August 2012 |work= Heritage Railway |publisher= Mortons Media Group Ltd. |accessdate= 5 December 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20131205111428/http://www.heritagerailway.co.uk/news/could-it-ever-be-better-than-this |archivedate= 5 December 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> the first time that a steam locomotive was recorded to have achieved 100&nbsp;mph.\n\nBetween the years of 1902 and 1908 he wrote a series of articles for ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' on British locomotive practice and performance. In 1990, these were collated and reprinted in book form.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |title=British Locomotive Practice & Performance\n  |first=Charles  |last=Rous-Marten\n  |authorlink=:en:Charles Rous-Marten\n  |editor-first=Charles  |editor-last=Fryer\n  |publisher=[[:en:Patrick Stephens Limited|PSL]]\n  |isbn=1-85260-222-8\n  |year=1990\n}}</ref>\n\nHe married Miss Emily Jane Hickson in 1876; there were no children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://steamindex.com/authorsp.htm#rous-marten |title=Authorship of railway literature |work=steamindex.com |accessdate=2014-05-07}}\n* {{cite web | title = Obituary: Charles Rous-Marten| author = The Engineer | url = http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/images/5/5f/Er19080424a.pdf | accessdate=2015-02-08 | pages = 431 | date = April 24, 1908}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* Charles Rous-Martin at WorldCat [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-rous%20marten,%20charles/ 1] [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-rous%20marten,%20charles$1841%201908/ 2], [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-marten,%20charles%20rous/ 3]\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/EP19080422.2.72?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Evening Post in Papers Past |date=22 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19080423.2.41?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Dominion in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/GEST19080423.2.37?end_date=31-05-1908&page=2&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Greymouth Evening Star in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/ODT19080423.2.53?end_date=31-05-1908&page=2&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Otago Daily Times in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19080423.2.51?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= New Zealand Herald in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/OW19080429.2.136?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Otago Witness in Papers Past |date=29 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/CHP19080529.2.26?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Personal Items re successor |publisher= Press in Papers Past |date=29 May 1908 }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rous-Marten, Charles}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from influenza]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Rail transport writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n[[File:Charles Rous-Marten.jpg|thumb|Photograph of Charles Rous-Marten from his Obituary in The Engineer]]'''Charles Rous-Marten''' (1842\u20131908) was a New Zealand journalist and British railway writer and recorder.\n\nHe was born in England. At the age of 16 his family emigrated to New Zealand, settling in [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]]. In 1864 he was appointed Meteorological Director of [[Southland Province]],<ref>''Southland Times'', 18 Oct 1864, p.5</ref> a position he held until 1870. He was employed as a journalist with ''[[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]]'' in Wellington about 1876 and was later editor, resigning in 1884. He was editor of ''[[The New Zealand Times]]'', also in Wellington, from 1885 to 1890. In that year he was appointed London correspondent for a number of leading New Zealand newspapers in the New Zealand Associated Press, which he continued to do until shortly before he died.<ref>''Press'', 23 Apr 1908, p.7</ref>\n\nHe took a close interest in railways over many years and in 1884 and 1885 he did a thorough study of the British rail network, involving around 40,000 miles of travel. In 1887 the results were embodied in a report to the New Zealand Minister of Public Works entitled [http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-52019982/view;''Notes on the Railways of Great Britain''], which received favourable reviews.<ref>''Otago Daily Times'', 9 Jul 1908, p.12</ref>\n\nHe is chiefly known for recording a speed of 102.3&nbsp;mph on the 'Ocean Mail' special from Plymouth to London hauled by [[Great Western Railway|GWR]] locomotive [[GWR 3700 Class 3440 City of Truro|3440 City of Truro]] on 9 May 1904,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.heritagerailway.co.uk/news/could-it-ever-be-better-than-this |title= Could it ever be better than this? |date= 6 August 2012 |work= Heritage Railway |publisher= Mortons Media Group Ltd. |accessdate= 5 December 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20131205111428/http://www.heritagerailway.co.uk/news/could-it-ever-be-better-than-this |archivedate= 5 December 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> the first time that a steam locomotive was recorded to have achieved 100&nbsp;mph.\n\nBetween the years of 1902 and 1908 he wrote a series of articles for ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' on British locomotive practice and performance. In 1990, these were collated and reprinted in book form.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |title=British Locomotive Practice & Performance\n  |first=Charles  |last=Rous-Marten\n  |authorlink=:en:Charles Rous-Marten\n  |editor-first=Charles  |editor-last=Fryer\n  |publisher=[[:en:Patrick Stephens Limited|PSL]]\n  |isbn=1-85260-222-8\n  |year=1990\n}}</ref>\n\nHe married Miss Emily Jane Hickson in 1876; there were no children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://steamindex.com/authorsp.htm#rous-marten |title=Authorship of railway literature |work=steamindex.com |accessdate=2014-05-07}}\n* {{cite web | title = Obituary: Charles Rous-Marten| author = The Engineer | url = http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/images/5/5f/Er19080424a.pdf | accessdate=2015-02-08 | pages = 431 | date = April 24, 1908}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* Charles Rous-Martin at WorldCat [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-rous%20marten,%20charles/ 1] [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-rous%20marten,%20charles$1841%201908/ 2], [http://worldcat.org/identities/np-marten,%20charles%20rous/ 3]\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/EP19080422.2.72?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Evening Post in Papers Past |date=22 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19080423.2.41?end_date=31-05-1908&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Dominion in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/GEST19080423.2.37?end_date=31-05-1908&page=2&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Greymouth Evening Star in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|url= https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/ODT19080423.2.53?end_date=31-05-1908&page=2&query=Rous-Marten&start_date=01-04-1908 |title= Obituary |publisher= Otago Daily Times in Papers Past |date=23 April 1908 }}\n*{{cite web|